observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The MBO immediately stop the practice of charging obligations without valid commitments and to obligate only those transactions which the Municipality has legal obligation/commitment to pay as evidenced by duly executed and/or conformed contracts/purchase orders and its related supporting documents;
The MA immediately stop recognizing Construction in Progress (CIP) and Accounts Payable (AP) on the basis only of the obligation drawn by the MBO. Instead recognize CIP and AP at an amount commensurate to the actual work accomplished based on the approved work accomplishment/SWA/progress billing/ inspection report and other relevant documents, among others, in line with the policies of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs;
The MA make adjusting journal entries to correct the erroneous recognition of CIP, AP and all related accounts as noted, in order to bring the account to its appropriate balances;
The MA reclassify those completed projects still included as CIP to its appropriate PPE accounts. Compute for the depreciation reckoned from the date of their completion, and draw adjusting journal entries by debiting prior period adjustments for unrecorded depreciation expense and crediting accumulated depreciation; and
The OME henceforth, furnish the MA with the Annual (Year-end) Accomplishment/Status Report on Government PPAs supported with SWA, inspection report, certificate of completion and acceptance, and/or other relevant documents, so that those completed and/or on-going projects with approved work accomplished as of year-end but not yet billed by the contractor, may be taken up in the books in its appropriate PPE or CIP accounts and the corresponding AP be set-up as at year-end.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant immediately issue official demand to concerned AOs with unliquidated cash advances for its immediate liquidation. Failure to comply thereto shall cause the suspension of their salaries until such time they have fully comply with the demand;
Create a fact-finding committee/team to conduct investigation on the noted issuance of OR without actual cash in an attempt to show that the excess/unclaimed cash advance was refunded, for appropriate action thereof;
The Municipal Treasurer ensure that cash advances of all disbursing officers under his direct supervision are timely liquidated in accordance with the deadline as provided in Item 5.1 of COA Circular No. 97-002 and any excess thereon are duly refunded and accounted immediately to properly safeguard government funds from misappropriation/misuse; and
Henceforth, strictly enforce to all accountable officers the liquidation of their cash advances within the reglementary period to prevent accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and to promote timely recording in the books of accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
During system’s failure, upgrade, or any situation which ETRACS becomes unavailable for use, the IT Department should make a written advisory/notice to the Municipal Treasurer for dissemination to concerned treasury divisions, copy furnished the Accountant Office and Office of the Auditor, for information, transparency and basis for manual issuances/preparation of ORs/RCDs;
Upon return of the system, the IT Department should likewise make a written advisory/notice to the Municipal Treasurer for dissemination with the concerned division and offices (same as above) for information, transparency and basis for batch capturing of those manually issued ORs. The manual RCDs shall be attached to the system’s generated RCDs for reference and continuity of the systems reports. The preparation of abstract of collection by the Review Unit Division should follow the actual dates of its collections/remittances based on the manually prepared RCDs;
Any request for corrections/adjustments in ETRACS reports to the IT Department should be made in writing duly signed by the requester, recommended for approval by the direct supervisor and approved by the Municipal Treasurer for proper authorization and future reference in accounting/auditing;
The Review Unit Division ensure that all RCDs submitted by the Cash Unit Division were reconciled to the list of remitted/liquidated RCDs by the CO/LO as reflected in the ETRACS to ensure that all collections/remittances during the day are accounted in the Abstract of Collection;
The LO prior to signing the “Verification and Acknowledgment” section of the RCD, ensure that same was duly verified not only as to amount of collections being remitted but ensure that the ending balances of accountable forms reflected therein are reconciled with the physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the CO in order to prevent/detect unreported manually issued ORs, if any;
Create a fact-finding committee/team to conduct investigation on the noted collections/remittances which were not timely deposited since allegedly borrowed by some municipal employees, for appropriate action thereof;
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant reconcile the noted difference of ₱4.427 million by comparing their respective records in order to identify the cause of such difference and effect the necessary and applicable adjustments/corrections to come up with the accurate Cash-Local Treasury account balance;
The Municipal Treasurer to closely monitor and ensure that all remittances are deposited regularly and intact daily or the next banking day by the Cashier with the LGU’s authorized depository bank; and
The Municipal Treasurer to strictly monitor and supervise compliance of all accountable officers under his direct supervision to the applicable laws, rules, and regulations in the collections and deposits with the end view of ensuring that all government funds are safeguarded from loss, misuse or misappropriation and prevent falsified collections.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The LFC adopt reasonable estimates of income as this would be used as basis in the budget formulation and ensure that income estimates are realistic or have an equitable assurance of being realized. In doing so, analyse the trend using past data and other economic factors or indicators that may likely affect or influence income projection;
The Municipal Treasurer prepare the Quarterly Report of Receipts or LBAc1, instead of the Statement of Receipts, certified correct by the Municipal Accountant and submit the same to the LFC, thru the MBO, in compliance with the requirement of the 2016 Budget Operations Manual;
For monthly monitoring purposes, it is recommended that the same format (LBAc1) should be used by the MT and MA, instead of the separate statement/report, for uniform and accurate presentation of figures and sound financial planning; and
As essential control in the release of allotment and incurrence of obligation, the MBO together with the MT and MA should closely monitor the actual receipts on a monthly basis such that if there is a significant shortfall in the projected/budgeted income, deferment of non-priority expenditures and non-release of allotments should be strictly observed.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Stop the practice of incurring obligations without corresponding cash back-up to avoid incurrence of further cash deficiency;
Intensify collection of outstanding receivables for real property and special education taxes to augment and increase cash inflows and design strategies to ensure that delinquent taxes are collected to cover the existing cash deficit;
Immediately implement other corrective measures to ensure adequacy of cash to meet its existing obligations to prevent possible penalties, surcharges and most of all legal implications in case the municipality would be unable to meet its obligations; and
The Municipal Treasurer prepare a Cash Position Report, segregated by mandatory allocation or fund (20%DF, LDRRMF, Continuing Appropriation, etc.) in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that disbursements are properly prioritized, managed and controlled.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The MEEDO include the construction of storage in its 2026 budget proposal. Meanwhile, continually look for a suitable temporary storage area of the machine to ensure its safety and operational efficiency;
Require the contractor to immediately pay the liquidated damages of ₱169,150.00;
The Municipal General Services and Municipal Accountant strictly monitor the delays in the delivery of goods, items and the like, and imposed the liquidated damages, as warranted;
Rescind contract in case the liquidated damages thereof exceeded the ten percent of the contract price and forfeit the supplier’s performance security.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Immediately stop charging travelling/training expenses and mobile allowances to the Special Education Fund which are not directly related to the maintenance and operation of public schools;
Refund the mobile allowances paid to municipal department heads, sangguniang bayan members who are provided with the same communication expenses/allowance under general fund;
For LSB Members who are DepEd officials/employees, submit duly signed certification (original copy) from the DepEd Division Accountant that such official/employee did not received the same communication expenses/allowance from DepEd regular budget, otherwise, the same should also be refunded to the SEF;
The LSB ensure that the programs, projects and activities included in their annual budget are strictly in line with the enumerated allowable expenses/expenditures as provided in DepEd-DILG-DBM Joint Circular No. 1 s. 2017 and its related addendums, and Sections 100 and 272 of RA No. 7160; and
The Municipal Budget Officer, Accountant and Treasurer ensure that only those communication and utility expenses of public schools or learning centers are charged to the SEF and henceforth, ensure that the disbursements charged against the fund are in accordance with the aforementioned law and DepEd-DILG-DBM joint circulars.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accounting and Municipal Treasurer’s Offices remit intact to BIR, GSIS, Pag-Ibig and PhilHealth all the contributions and/or loan amortizations withheld and within the respective prescribed period to avoid penalties/surcharges;
The Municipal Accountant make verification, analysis, and validation of the noted over-remittances or negative difference in the Due to PhilHealth account. Should it be established that there is indeed over remittance, make representation with the concerned agency for its refund, or enforce payment from the concerned/liable personnel if the same is caused by non-withholding;
Trace up the details of the noted long outstanding Due to GSIS, Pag-Ibig and Philhealth balances under SEF and TF and make the necessary adjustments, as appropriate.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Accounting Office, in coordination with the GSO, exert more effort in establishing the details of those unreconciled PPEs and same be included in its PPELCs maintained in order to ensure that balances of PPEs appearing on the financial statements are supported and reconciled with the balances reflected in the PPELCs;
The Appraisal and Inventory Committee conduct physical count of all PPEs  including PPEs like Land, Land Improvements, Infrastructure Assets, and Buildings and Other Structures, and ensure that RPCPPE is prepared and signed in accordance with the requirement prescribed in Volume II of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs;
The GSO and the Accounting Office conduct reconciliation of their PPE records (PCs and PPELCs) to ascertain the discrepancy and to make the necessary adjustments, if any; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts pursuant to Commission on Audit (COA) Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Reconciliation of records and documents on file between the Office of the Municipal Accountant and the GSO should be done and updated regularly to ascertain that the recorded balance in the books of the Municipality is valid and accurate;
Prioritize the immediate registration and titling of unregistered/untitled lots acquired through purchase or donation in the name of the Municipality to properly safeguard its interest and so that ownership thereof would be absolute and established for all legal intents and purposes;
Recognize in the book those land that were acquired through decrees, deeds or court decisions at its cost based on the available document or fair market value, if not available; and
The Municipal Planning and Development Council ensure that improvements and public infrastructures are constructed on the lot absolutely owned by the Municipality.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The MDRRMO:
Cease incurring further repairs on fully depreciated rescue vehicles, instead consider the procurement of brand new rescue vehicles which is more prudent and economical on the part of the government;
Strictly observe the protocol of subjecting all damaged vehicles for pre-repair inspection by the GSO so that proper assessment/evaluation of its necessity and condition be made and ensure that the purchase request for needed parts are duly approved; and
Ensure that all replaced parts and waste materials from the repairs are presented and surrendered to the GSO upon post-repair inspection for its proper disposal and to ascertain that parts requested were really installed and repairs are actually undertaken.
The GSO:
Designate an authorized inspector who has the expertise in evaluating the needed repairs for damaged vehicles and have his/her signature in the pre-repair and post repair documents;
Stop the practice of signing pre-repair and post repair documents and other pertinent documents without actually conducting inspection, assessment and evaluation thereof. Repair transactions which does not course through the proper control route should not be processed;
Ensure that all PCs of vehicles/equipment of the municipality were regularly updated as these will serve as basis in evaluating the necessity and extent of repair and identifying vehicles/equipment that are beyond economic repair;
Kept custody and control over the waste materials for its proper disposal and look for available warehouse which will serve as its storage; and
Prepare a written policy on repairs of vehicles/equipment taking into consideration the allowable limit of repairs under COA Circular No. 2012-003 in coordination with other concerned departments, subject for approval of the Local Chief Executive.
The Municipal Accountant:
Ensure that disbursements for repair and maintenance of vehicles/equipment are supported with its corresponding repair history;
Record in the books the PTV Ambulance acquired on March 4, 2022 and prepare its corresponding ledger card;
Together with the GSO and all offices concerned, conduct a cost-benefit analysis of all vehicles/equipment of the municipality and consider disposal of fully depreciated and outmoded vehicles/equipment that are beyond economic repair which incur unnecessary and excessive costs. If warranted, procure brand new vehicles/equipment as a replacement; and
Refrain from spending repair expenditures which are unnecessary, excessive and unconscionable to avoid issuance of Notice of Disallowance.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant comply with the documentary requirements in the granting and liquidation of cash advances for payment of honoraria to RPs/Instructors as provided in COA Circular No. 2012-001;
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) Secretariat ensure that the Result of Eligibility Check/Screening and Post Qualification Report on all procured projects subjected for bidding is attached as part of the supporting documents of its related disbursements;
The Municipal Engineer ensure the submission by the Contractor of the As-built plan upon completion of infrastructure projects and the Municipal Accountant ensure that same is part of the supporting documents for final payment; and
The Municipal Engineer ensure that pictures of on-going construction projects implemented by administration is properly documented and same should form part of the supporting documents in the payment of labor.

Instruct the Review Unit Division and the assigned Information Technology personnel to update in the RAAF/CRAAF all AFs that have been issued based on the manual RCDs in order to reflect its correct balances;

Make representation with the system provider for updating the system in order to capture the actual inclusive serial numbers of the AFs balances in the generated RAAF/CRAAF. Pending compliance thereof, advise the AOs to make necessary corrections with their initials for unreconciled quantity and serial numbers of  AFs in their individual RAAF, and the same shall be the basis of the Review Unit Division in reconciling the CRAAF;

Strictly enforce the submission of the individual RAAF of each AOs and instruct the Review Unit Division to reconcile the same with the generated CRAAF in order to ensure completeness and accuracy of the report;

Ensure that all obsolete, spoiled or cancelled checks are properly indicated in the RAAF/CRAAF and the Report on obsolete, spoiled and cancelled accountable forms are prepared/maintained and submitted to this office;

Include all checks receipts, issuances and balances in the RAAF/CRAAF for proper monitoring of accountability for checks;

Trace up the non-moving cash tickets and make the necessary corrections/adjustments in the RAAF/CRAAF; and

Make use of the CRAAF in formulating preventive and detective controls/measures in the management of fund and immediately act upon noted deficiencies/irregularities in order to prevent unremitted collections, misuse/misappropriations of funds.

The Municipal Accountant expedite the identification of unreconciled balances of “Due to NGAs”, “Due to LGUs” and “TL-DRRMF” accounts;

The Municipal Social Welfare and Development (MSWD) Office submit RDSs of the remaining bags of rice that will be distributed duly supported with inventory report and certified list from the barangay;

The Facilitator of the subject training submit the acknowledgement/ distribution sheets for the remaining 50 disaster kits;

The MSWD Office provide sufficient evidence/supporting documents to establish that the recipients of the financial assistance are indeed resident of the barangay as indicated in its corresponding payroll; and

The Municipal Accountant ensure henceforth, that all disbursements particularly in the seminar/trainings/orientations conducted by the municipality are supported with Office Order, Course Outline, Certified and Validated Attendance Sheets, and all other supporting documents relevant and sufficient thereto.

The General Services Office ensure that pictures taken for each procurement can be identified and quantified with the PO;

The MSWD Office ensure that RDSs are:

properly labeled as to name of the project and source/s of fund;

completely filled out by indicating all the necessary information in the distribution sheets particularly the specific goods and quantity of item distributed; and

signed by authorized personnel/official; 

The MSWD Office provide supporting documents relative to the inconsistency noted between the logbook of relief packs versus procured items per PO/RIS;

The MSWD Office gather updated data of the beneficiaries’ profile during the planning phase of the procurement to ensure adequate and appropriate procurement of relief goods and to avoid excess stock of procured items;

The MSWD Office prepare an inventory report of undistributed or remaining items, if any, every end of the project/activity and submit the same to the GSO for control and monitoring, copy furnish the Office of the Auditor;

The MSWD Office conduct monitoring of undistributed goods on stock in consideration with the succeeding procurement of relief goods; and

The MSWD Office ensure to indicate in the project/activity design sources of relief goods other than the procurement at hand, if any, such as the items and quantity to be taken from stock/undistributed items, and other sufficient information necessary in the conduct of audit.

The Human Resource Management and Development Office (HRMDO) prepare a complete organizational structure that includes JO/CoS to determine the needed personnel and competencies in accomplishing and achieving targets and deliverables of various offices;

The HRMDO evaluate the actual manpower complement of all the Departments/Offices and re-assess the necessity of JO/CoS workers therein, particularly in the department/office with high percentage of JO/CoS workers over plantilla personnel, and remove or re-assign excessive and unnecessary JOs/CoS workers who are performing redundant functions with other workers and regular plantilla personnel;

The HRMDO provide specific job/task to be performed per designation in the job order contract or prepare statement of duties and responsibility per designation to be conformed by the concerned worker upon hiring to serve as basis in assessing their accomplishment reports;

The HRMDO provide specific detail such as place/unit/division/shift of assignment in the Job Order contract or contract of service;

The HRMDO coordinate with the Internal Audit Services to formulate guidelines, policies and procedures in the hiring of JO/CoS workers; and

The concerned Department Heads, Municipal Accountant and Internal Audit Services of the Municipality ensure that the claims for JOs/CoS are supported with properly reviewed and valid accomplishment reports in accordance with their assigned duties and responsibilities to avoid generic, repetitive and/or copy paste accomplishment reports.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
The Accounting Office exert more effort in tracing back those PPEs recorded in the financial statements but not supported with PPELC so that the same will be included in the PPELCs maintained and ensure that balances of PPEs appearing on the financial statements are supported and reconciled with the balances reflected in the PPELC;
The Property Inventory, Appraisal, and Disposal Committee conduct the physical count of PPEs including other PPEs like Land, Land Improvements, Infrastructure Assets and Buildings and Other Structures, and present the same in the RPCPPE;
The GSO include in the preparation of PC other PPEs like Land, Land Improvements, Infrastructure Assets and Buildings and Other Structures in the PC, and coordinate with the Accounting Office the cost of those constructed PPEs, if not available, request the Property Inventory, Appraisal, and Disposal Committee to determine its market value;
The GSO and the Accounting Office conduct reconciliation of their PPE records (PC and PPELC) to ascertain the discrepancy and to make the necessary adjustments in order to establish the completeness, accuracy and existence of the PPE accounts presented in the Financial Statements; and
The Property Inventory, Appraisal, and Disposal Committee properly prepare and submit the RPCPPE to facilitate smooth identification and verification of properties and its balances.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant compute the appropriate depreciation expenses for the ₱15.612 million PPE and make the necessary adjusting entries to update/correct the accumulated depreciation by debiting depreciation expense (for the current year’s depreciation) and prior year’s adjustment (for the prior year’s depreciation) and crediting accumulated depreciation (for the total unrecorded depreciation);
Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant see to it that all depreciable properties owned by the LGU are provided with depreciation in accordance with the above-mentioned rules and regulations to ensure its fair presentation in the financial statements;
The Inventory Committee ensure that the items and amount presented in the RPCPPE are correct/accurate and the RPCPPE are properly prepared by type for easy reconciliation; and
The General Services Office and the Accounting Office expedite the reconciliation of their PPE records to ascertain their differences and will make the necessary adjustments in order to establish the completeness, accuracy and existence of the PPE accounts presented in the Financial Statements;

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant furnish the bank a copy of the Bank Reconciliation Statements and inform them of the items requiring adjustments by the bank, coupled with complete supporting documents;
The Municipal Accountant verify and review outstanding checks which have become stale and make the appropriate adjusting entries in their books;
Expedite the request for the cancellation of the bank service charges totaling to ₱40,429.78. Otherwise, these will be the personal liability and should be refunded by the accountable officer(s) liable for its incurrence; and
The Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant reconcile their records/books to determine any necessary corrections and henceforth, to conduct a regular reconciliation of their balances so that the adjustments made or errors detected either by the Treasury or Accounting Office will be timely adjusted and posted in their respective books; and
The Municipal Accountant include in the BRS reconciliation of cashbook balances with that of the ledger and bank balances.

We recommended and the management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant make the necessary adjusting entries on the affected inventory accounts to properly account for the receipt and issuance of the relief goods and henceforth, be more diligent in the proper recording/accounting of transactions based on the source documents to provide fairly stated account balances;
The General Services Office ensure the timely preparation of RIS and SSMI which should be submitted to the Municipal Accountant weekly and conduct year-end physical count of inventory items, in coordination with the MSWDO, to determine the undistributed /unconsumed items and the cost of these items shall be restored back to the inventory account; and
Provide for a designated stock room to properly store and secure the relief goods in stocks of the municipality;
The MSWDO observe the following: Trace up/reconcile the unaccounted balance of 3,883 sacks of rice and require the concerned officials to have the signature of the 283 recipients to acknowledge their receipt of the relief goods and have the RDSs be duly signed by the concerned/in-charge officials; Henceforth, ensure that all RDSs were fully filled out and duly signed to provide sufficient and reliable information and promote transparency especially on the items and quantity of the relief goods to be received by the beneficiaries; and
Maintain a registry per article/item of goods to monitor/track its issuance and balances and to prepare and maintain a separate logbook to record the receipt of relief goods for distribution per sources of funds.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive the following:
Ensure that the Municipal Budget Officer, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer coordinate closely in monitoring the cash position of the municipality to ensure that all disbursements are properly manage and control to avoid incurrence of cash overdraft and obligations be paid accordingly;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert extra effort to work back and reconcile the balances to ensure that there are available resources for expenditures and the currently maturing obligations. Closely monitor the cash balance against expenditures to be incurred to avoid cash overdraft.

We recommended the following:
Prioritize the implementation of the immediate rehabilitation and closure of the Municipal Disposal Site following the conditions embodied in the Authority to Close issued by the DENR;
As an alternative, continually look for sanitary landfill sites that shall be developed and operated as a final disposal site for solid and, eventually, residual wastes of the municipality in compliance with the Solid Waste Management Act;
Adapt an Alternative Technology that shall process collected residual waste into a resource or new products/materials such as hollow blocks, eco-bricks, planks or aggregate to construction materials to avoid congestion of unprocessed residual wastes in the facility;
Re-evaluate the operation of the Materials Recovery Facility in Barangay Bakhaw Sur and effect the necessary changes and actions in accordance with its proper usage and procedures. Strict monitoring, supervision and control must be applied to the personnel assigned in the Disposal Site/MRF as well as to the registered waste pickers in their waste picking and sorting activities.

a. Direct the Accountant to prepare and effect the necessary adjustments on the unrecorded transactions/reconciling items identified in the Bank Reconciliation Statements. In cases, wherein adjustments require supporting documents or action by person/s other than herself, she should communicate officially to the concerned official or employee to ensure their immediate action;
b. Require the refund of ₱3,830.00 from the person(s) responsible for the issuance of check with insufficient fund;
c. Demand from the bank the refund/adjustment of ₱1,580.00 erroneous bank debit of other entity’s check as well as of the ₱34,109.82 bank debit. And establish the documentary evidence on the unrecorded deposit of ₱24,995.31 on November 30, 2017 in the bank and demand the credit of the same; and
d. As a matter of remedy and/or option, the Accountant establish intra receivable and payable account then make the transfer of the amount from the erroneous bank account to the should be bank account in order to expedite the adjustments of Cash in Bank balance on reconciling items which involves adjustments between agency’s bank accounts within the same bank.

